questiontext.text: Which of the following are vectors? Select all that apply.

generalfeedback.text: A scalar quantity is fully described by magnitude only. A vector quantity is fully described by both magnitude and direction. Distance, speed, and time are scalars. Acceleration, displacement, and velocity are vectors.

questiontext.text: A scalar quantity is fully described by

generalfeedback.text: A scalar quantity is fully described by magnitude alone.

questiontext.text: Suppose an object travels at a constant velocity of 56.0 km/h. What distance would it travel in 78.0 minutes?

generalfeedback.text:
Use the formula for constant velocity motion making sure to convert to the proper units.

\[ d = vt = (\SI{56.0}{km/h})(\SI{78.0}{min})\left(\frac{\SI{1}{h}}{\SI{60}{min}} \right) = 72.8 \,\mathsf{km}\]

questiontext.text: A car travels at for and for and . How far does it travel in this time?

generalfeedback.text:
Use the formula for constant velocity motion for each part and add the two distances together.

\[ d = v_1 t_1 + v_2 t_2 = (\SI{50}{km/h})(\SI{0.5}{h}) + (\SI{80}{km/h})(\SI{1.25}{h}) = \SI{125}{km}\]

questiontext.text: Suppose an object travels at a constant velocity of \(\SI{13.6}{m/s}\). What distance would it travel in \(\SI{68.7}{s}\)?

generalfeedback.text:
Use the formula for constant velocity motion.

\[ d = vt = (\SI{13.6}{m/s})(\SI{68.7}{s}) = \SI{934}{m}\]

questiontext.text: How many seconds would it take the Sun’s light to reach Earth? The speed of light in vacuum is \(3.0 \times 10^8\) m/s. The Sun is \(1.5 \times 10^{11}\) m from the Earth.

generalfeedback.text:
Use the formula for constant velocity motion.

\[ t = \frac{d}{v} = \frac{\SI{1.5E11}{m}}{\SI{3E8}{m/s}} = \SI{5.0E2}{s}\]

questiontext.text:
A light-year () is the distance that light travels in vacuum in one year.
The speed of light is . How many miles are there in a light-year?

(\(\SI{1}{mile} = \SI{1.609E3}{\meter}\), \(\SI{1}{year} = \SI{365}{days}\))

generalfeedback.text:
Use the formula for constant velocity motion and convert to the desired units.

\[(\SI{1}{yr}) \left(\frac{\SI{365}{days}}{\SI{1}{yr}}\right) \left(\frac{\SI{24}{h}}{\SI{1}{day}}\right) \left(\frac{\SI{60}{min}}{\SI{1}{h}}\right) \left(\frac{\SI{60}{s}}{\SI{1}{min}}\right) = \SI{3.1536e+07}{s}\]

\[ d = vt = (\SI{3.00E8}{m/s})(\SI{3.1536e+07}{s}) = \SI{9.4608e+15}{m}\] \[(\SI{9.4608e+15}{m}) \left(\frac{\SI{1}{mi}}{\SI{1.609E3}{m}}\right) = \SI{5.88e+12}{mi}\]

questiontext.text: A car travels at and at . What is the average speed for this trip?

generalfeedback.text:
The average speed is the total distance divided by the total time.

\[ v_{avg} = \frac{d_{total}}{t_{total}} = \frac{d_1 + d_2}{d_1/v_1 + d_2/v_2} = \frac{\SI{35}{km} + \SI{288}{km}}{\frac{\SI{35}{km}}{\SI{21}{km/h}} + \frac{\SI{288}{km}}{\SI{100}{km/h}}} = \SI{71}{km/h}\]

questiontext.text:
Which position-time graph represents an object at rest?

Graph A Graph B Graph C Graph D

generalfeedback.text: An object at rest has zero velocity so the slope of its position-time graph must have a slope of zero (horizontal line).

questiontext.text: What is the magnitude of the slope of a position-time graph?

generalfeedback.text: The magnitude of the slope of a position-time graph is the speed of the object.

questiontext.text: Which choice best matches the given position-time graph?

generalfeedback.text:
The object is moving to the right if its position is increasing and moving to the left if its position is decreasing. The object is speeding up if the tangent line is becoming more vertical and slowing down if the tangent line is becoming more horizontal.

This graph describes an object that is moving to the right and speeding up.

answer.text: moving to the right and speeding up.
moving to the right and slowing down.
moving to the left and speeding up.
moving to the left and slowing down.

questiontext.text:
Which velocity-time graph represents motion with constant positive acceleration?

Graph A Graph B Graph C Graph D

generalfeedback.text: Acceleration is the slope of the velocity-time graph. Therefore, the correct answer is the graph with the positive slope. Note that for positive acceleration it does not matter if the velocity is always negative as long as the slope is positive.
